04027nam a22005175i 9780520967526DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209675267 a10.1525/97805209675262doi  a(DE-B1597)520737  a(OCoLC)1003489580  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020002bisacsh1 aFerme, Mariane C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aOut of War :bViolence, Trauma, and the Political Imagination in Sierra Leone /cMariane C. Ferme. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Belatedness -- tChronotope 1: Prefiguring Shifting Alliances-The Sobel -- t2. Wartime Rumors -- tChronotope 2: Numbers, Examples, and Exceptions -- t3. Hunters, Warriors, and Their Technologies -- t4. Sitting on the Land -- t5. Refugees and Diasporic Publics -- t6. Child Soldiers and the Contested Imaginary of Community after War -- t7. Forced Marriage and Sexual Enslavement -- t8. Inscriptions on the Wall -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOut of War draws on Mariane C. Ferme's three decades of ethnographic engagements to examine the physical and psychological aftereffects of the harms of Sierra Leone's civil war. Ferme analyzes the relationship between violence, trauma, and the political imagination, focusing on "war times"-the different qualities of temporality arising from war. She considers the persistence of precolonial and colonial figures of sovereignty re-elaborated in the context of war, and the circulation of rumors and neologisms that freeze in time collective anxieties linked to particular phases of the conflict (or "chronotopes"). Beyond the expected traumas of war, Ferme explores the breaks in the intergenerational transmission of farming and hunting techniques, and the lethal effects of remembering experienced traumas and forgetting local knowledge. In the context of massive population displacements and humanitarian interventions, this ethnography traces strategies of survival and material dwelling, and the juridical creation of new figures of victimhood, where colonial and postcolonial legacies are reinscribed in neoliberal projects of decentralization and individuation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aWarxPsychological aspects. 70(DE-601)1043601780(DE-588)4008784-0aBürgerkrieg2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520967526.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles